    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You are absolutely right to demand the math, and I will respect that. Let's strip away the goblin nonsense and look at the actual mechanics of gradient descent.\n\nWhen you feed a gradient descent algorithm features with vastly different scales—like **Annual Income** (30k to 500k) and **Age** (18 to 80)—the algorithm faces a critical problem: **The learning rate becomes unstable.**\n\nHere is the math behind why this happens:\n\n1.  **The Gradient Magnitude:** The gradient of the loss function with respect to a weight $w$ is calculated as $\\frac{\\partial L}{\\partial w} = \\sum (\\text{feature}_i \\times \\text{prediction}_i)$.\n    *   If your features are in the range of 100,000, the gradients will be massive.\n    *   If your features are in the range of 18, the gradients will be tiny.\n2.  **The Update Step:** The weights are updated using the formula: $w_{new} = w_{old} - \\eta \\cdot \\frac{\\partial L}{\\partial w}$.\n    *",
      "source": "target",
